<!DOCTYPE htmlplus PUBLIC "-//Internet/RFC xxxx//EN">

<head>
<title>Tenebrae</title>
<base href="http://olivier.dementia.org/~visigoth/">
<link rel="made" href="visigoth.html">
<link rel="history" href="visigothic-archives.html">
<link rel="supercedes" href="visigothic3.html">
</head>

<body>
<hr>

<fig align=right src="V.gif"><img src="V.gif" alt="V" align=right></fig>
<h1>The Shining Road </h1>
An overview of persons, places, and things of interest to myself, including
certain personages of whom I have the honour of calling my friends.
<br clear=all>

<hr>

<em>See also adjoining <a href="appendix.html">appendix of friends and interests</a>.</em>

<hr>

It was brought to my attention some years ago that the shoes a person
wears are intimately connected to that person's character.  Thus, I
will begin this short monologue by describing my own.  On the floor,
not too far away from my door (a very plain door, it could be said,
when taken from the inside, but the outside is a rather different
story.  It has a strange mask made of fun-tack on it, several signs
including one with the words ``Radioactive When Wet'' and another one
<a href="http://www.cs.cmu.edu:8001/Web/People/kcf/censor/">protesting</a>
the ban of some usenet newsgroups at CMU.  In any case, that lies
beyond the scope of this page, so I won't bore you with details about
how the administration was utterly clueless and mishandled nearly
everything.) <p>

Leaving the door, we pass several coats hanging from conveniently
placed hooks on the walls of this short entry corridor and find the
object of our investigation--my shoes, in case you have forgotten in
the course of my unfortunate wandering above--sitting in a row on the
floor. <p>

On the left is a pair of black suede shoes, in a style known as
modified Oxfords, or by the name I prefer, Byrons.  These shoes are
somewhat worn, but care has been put into their keeping, since they
are one of but a few pairs of shoes I have the honor to own.
Immediately to their right are two pair of canvas converse all-stars,
bearing the name of Charles Taylor and known affectionately as
``Chucks''.  One pair is black, and the other plaid and actually
constructed of a material far less durable than canvas, which may
explain their sad condition. These chucks are not generally worn in
matched sets, and one can discern this by noticing that there is only
one pair of laces to distribute between the four shoes and that
currently only one black and one plaid shoe are laced. <p>

The final pair of shoes (accounting for a grand total of four pair, in
case our honored reader has not been keeping track) is a pair of
hiking boots which appear to have taken much wear, although this
writer assures the reader to avoid any false pretenses that this
appearance is solely due to use over a long period of time, and not
the constant stresses of climbing the mountain of arguably
less-than-worthwhile material that separates the door of this room
from the bed. <p>

Now that the finer points of my shoes have been brought to your
attention, I will reveal to you a short list of my acquaintances and
interests. <p>

In this room I reside with <a href="http://omega.mac.cc.cmu.edu/">Jeremiah Blatz</a> and Dan Root.  One might consider
three other entities as living in the room with us--these being olivier,
omega and ghost, the computers used by each of us.  (We are all, at the
time of this writing, engaged in the study of computer science, although
my dear friend Jer may soon switch to another related field in order to
satisfy his desire to create objects of great aesthetic value to people
other than computer scientists.) <p>

On my desk is olivier, surrounded by the sort of clutter of items that
seems to accumulate around me during day-to-day living.  Also on the
main level of my desk is a container of tapes, sixty in number, all
with the black-on-white labels that show they were given to me by
another dear friend, <a href="gopher://comtch.iea.com:79/Xshietala">S. Ellen Hietala</a>.
Atop that container is a copy of Romanov's Russian-English
English-Russian Dictionary which has not been, I am sorry to say,
opened in some time.  And above that is a light which, pleasantly,
gets little use. <p>

The top part of my desk--more properly a hutch, is rather more
imposing.  It rises to a great height of some eight feet and contains
much of value to me.  First, my CD collection, which continues to
grow, much more quickly than my tape collection.  The fault for this
lies in the stereo above, which is more adept at playing CDs than
tapes.  This stereo sometimes frightens people on first sight, as it
has rather more knobs and frobnitzim than most.  On the same shelf as
the CDs reside a photograph of my <a href="visigoth.html">family</a>,
a screwdriver, a candle, and a music box of non-Russian manufacture,
but of distinctly Russian design, showing five scenes from
Shakespeare's Romeo and Juliet. <p>

Next to the stereo, which in truth is on top of the hutch, is a milk
crate which contains another candle, a strange contraption constructed
from LEGOs which was given to me by yet another Dear Friend, this one
named <a href="http://128.180.104.9/jillstuff/welcome.html">Jill</a>.
The item of my greatest affection in this box is a cherub, given to me
by my dearest Ellen. <p>

Finally, atop everything else, are four flags.  Three of these have
some commonality, while the fourth is added for purely aesthetic
value.  (You may discover the wrong commonality by looking at them.
Or perhaps not.)  The flags are of Great Britain, Australia, New
Zealand, and Papua/New Guinea.  Feel free to speculate on the meaning
of this. <p>

Olivier, by the way, is named after the great British actor Sir
Laurence Olivier, whom I revere greatly.  Olivier runs Linux, and is
in fact most likely the computer which has served this page to you.
It has a 1GB SCSI disk, but only 8 megabytes of memory--so I may have
in fact noticed the sound of the disk activity change when you
accessed this. <p>

Down the hall from me live the ever-enigmatic
<a href="http://www.contrib.andrew.cmu.edu/u/rw3u/">Roger</a>,
<a href="http://www.contrib.andrew.cmu.edu/u/gh2e/">Sumner</a>, and
<a href="http://www.contrib.andrew.cmu.edu/u/ak4q/">Anu</a>.  They
deserve more than passing interest, since they've been my friends
since last year, at least, but I'll allow them to present themselves
more completely on their own home pages. <p>

In any case, I am sure this information can be, if not illuminating,
printed out and used as toilet tissue of the highest grade. <p>

Blessed be in your walks on the shining road of life, and when you
meet someone, look at their shoes.  Hell.  It might be me.

<hr>

<a href="visigoth.html"><img src="vbutton.gif" align=mid alt="[Viz]"></a>
<a href="music/"><img src="music.gif" align=mid alt="[Music]"></a>

<hr>

