<head>
<title> Visigothic - John McClary Prevost </title>
<base href="http://olivier.dementia.org/~visigoth/">
</head>

<body>
<fig align=center src="V.gif">
<center> <img src="V.gif" alt="V"> </center>
</fig>

<hr>

<img src="me2.gif" alt="[an Andrew toolkit image of some geek was here, but could not be displayed.]" align=left hspace=20 vspace=10>
<img src="me.gif" align=right hspace=20 vspace=10>
<center>
<h1> ``First Fig'' <br>
<cite> <font size=4> Edna St. Vincent Millay </font> </cite> </h1>

<quote>
I burn my candle at both ends,<br>
It will not last the night,<br>
But ah, my foes, and oh, my friends,<br>
It gives a lovely light!
</quote>
</center>

<br clear=all>

<hr>

<h1> A Russo-Gaelic Rennaisance Man </h1>

<p> Please allow me to introduce myself. My name is John McClary Prevost.
Throughout the years, I have been known by many other names. My
immediately family persists in calling me Jack, as they have done for
many many years, though I started going by John some while ago. When I
was on electronic bulletin boards, I called myself the Bishop, in
honor both of the chess piece and Harry Harrison's criminal
mastermind. Now I go by Visigoth... This name comes from my
fascination with things gothic (which I define in a slightly different
way than other people might), and my origins in the west.  Spokane to
be exact.  Spokane, Washington. </p>

<p> Spokane is the second largest city in Washington state. Second is,
of course, only a relative term. Relative to Seattle, one of the
larger cities in my part of the world. Especially if you consider the
other cities in the area that are inseperable from it to be part of
the whole. That is, however, immaterial. Spokane lies in the middle of
wheat country--the Palouse Hills. Several generations ago, my family
on my mother's side migrated to the area by way of the Oregon trail.
They were in a group of seven great families that settled the area
(Hamilton, Blish, Hodgen, Young, Pankey, and I can't remember the other two.)
Intermarriage occured, of course, since there weren't many other
groups in the area, and the families became a group.  This is why the
large family reunions that happened every two years come to mind when
I think about family.  </p>

<p> My mom's family is pretty much standard standard rural
american--straight-laced, football watching, country music listening
hicks. Not a bad bunch, but not my style. My mom avoided coming to be
just like them when she met my father.  (I am told they married after
knowing each other for less than a month, on the set of "The Taming of
the Shrew". They were somewhat hippieish, coming in on the end of that
era. The men at the wedding all wore formal dress with their hair tied
back with ribbons. I've seen pictures, and it was indeed a sight.) Anyway.  Dad was
raised as a city kid. His family comes from Detroit, but moved to
Spokane when he was young. His dad was a maniac (balding, as all the
Prevost men seem to be, and jolly, even though he hated to be called
Grandpa...  He wanted all us kids to call him "Doug" (his name), so we
called him Grandpa Doug.  He grew to accept this, though he never
really liked kids much.)  On the fourth of July, Grandpa Doug would
take old pipes and such and launch bottle rockets at the neighbors. He
was a socialist, and never worked to hide his views, nor did he keep
the <i>Russia Today</i> magazines that came to his door wrapped in
brown paper hidden. Doug was always fascinated by Russia. This is, I
suppose, where my fascination with Russia comes from.  </p>

<p> My father's mother, Grandma Shirley, was always quiet and
reserved, trying to hold a family of <em>very</em> opinionated people
together. Her parents were both Irish. The McClarys. They traveled to
Spokane via Canada, crossing from the Atlantic to the Pacific in three
generations. (My mom's family's history in the U.S.  goes back much
further.) All of her children except for one had red hair. I don't
have red hair--but my beard is red. This is, without a doubt, where my
fascination with Eire and things Celtic comes from.  </p>

<p> My father was raised Catholic (including Catholic school and the
like), and my mother was raised Lutheran. They raised my sister
Natalie and I to be agnostic.  It's anybody's guess what her religion
will end up as. I sincerely hope she remains agnostic. It's a good way
to be accepting, if you don't try to force it on others. Myself, I
have ended up with a rather Pagan viewpoint. My philosophy rules my
life much more than any religious belief, but if any gods do exist, I
believe that they are multiple. I also believe in force of will.
Whether that is magic or not, I cannot say. In essence--I do not
believe that my beliefs in this area effect whether I do good or not,
so I try to avoid worrying about it. I am, as in all things,
irreverant.  </p>

<p> I'm working right now as a Systems Programmer for facilities in
the CS department here at Carnegie Mellon. In the past, I've worked as
a consultant in the computer clusters, and I've done extensive work in
desktop publishing. Since I don't use Macs too much any more, I don't
know the quirks of the latest programs, but I like to think my grasp
on the ideals of page layout is still good. In my current job, I've
created a database for keeping track of CS department alumni, and a
software availability database listing what software is available for
what platforms in the department. I'm currenty the Linux support
person in the department, as well as the Linux SIG knight for the CMU
Student Computer Club, and generally one of the Linux gurus on campus.
I also like Perl.  In a recent development, I'm trying to attain
sufficient AIX clue to become the full-time AIX support person in the
department. As my friend Anu says: ``Staff-job having bastard? Stay
tuned!'' </p>

<p> I'm working on an archive of lyrics for my favorite bands... (The
music link off of these pages, with the dotted eighth note...) Check
back, occasionally. Feel free to mail me any ideas you have for links
to add to my poem, and I'll change the poem again one of these days.
</p>

<p> Oh--I've got some friends in the area, too...  Jer's my roommate.
Sidney's gone now, and Dan has moved in. Anu's kind of depressing
sometimes, but seems much happier lately. He likes owls. Jill's a
dear. Roger's something different. Ben's got good taste in music.
Sumner's a math major with too much time on his hands, and Mike's a
god. </p>

<p> There's a visigoth at Caltech on the west coast who's also into
Linux, but he's not me. I actually have no idea who he is. Because of
this, I go by Ostragoth on the very rare occasions that I use IRC.
</p>

<p> Peace, and Blessed Be.  </p>

<address>
John McClary Prevost <br>
Box 3032 <br>
1000 Morewood Avenue <br>
Pittsburgh, PA 15213 <br>
<br>
visigoth@olivier.dementia.org
</address>

</body>

