<head>
    <title>Fight-Censorship: [3042] FCC's Hundt says no "thoughtless regulation" of the Net</title>
    <link href="/fight-censorship/" rel="up">
    <link href="/~visigoth/" rel="made">
</head>
    
<body BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<fig src="rib_trn_plain_sm.gif" align=right>
    <p><img src="/~fight-censorship/rib_trn_plain_sm.gif" align=right alt="[Blue Ribbon]">
</fig>
    <h1>[3042] <a href="dl?thread=FCC's+Hundt+says+no+%22thoughtless+regulation%22+of+the+Net&after=3042">FCC's Hundt says no "thoughtless regulation" of the Net</a></h1>
    <h2><i>Declan McCullagh &lt;declan@eff.org&gt;</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: FCC's Hundt says no "thoughtless regulation" of the Net
<b>To</b>: fight-censorship+@andrew.cmu.edu
<b>From</b>: Declan McCullagh &lt;declan@eff.org&gt;
<b>Date</b>: Sun, 30 Jun 1996 18:40:04 -0700 (PDT)
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;Pine.SUN.3.91.960630182141.13968E-100000@eff.org&gt;

Reed Hundt's comments below on the ACTA petition and Internet telephony 
in general are encouraging, but I note he doesn't rule out all 
Net-regulation by the FCC. Instead, he just rules out "thoughtless" 
regulation.

Forwarded from cyber-rights.

-Declan


// declan@eff.org // I do not represent the EFF // declan@well.com //


---------- Forwarded message ----------
Date: Sun, 30 Jun 1996 14:24:46 -0700
From: andyo@ora.com

(This posting contains some of my personal opinions.)

FCC Chairman Reed Hundt has recently made statements indicating that
he supports Internet voice technology and is inclined to oppose the
petition that calls for its regulation.  This good news comes from the
Voice On the Net coalition (which represents companies offering
Internet voice technologies).  While Hundt does not indicate what
swayed him in the statements quoted below, I find it gratifying that
he makes essentially the same points emphasized by the CPSR comment to
the FCC.

The speech in its entirety is at the site:

	http://www.fcc.gov/Speeches/Hundt/spreh629.txt

Most of it sounds like a person who wants to talk himself out of a
job--it's all about letting the market determine what happens rather
than government regulation.

Andy

----------------------------------------------------------------------

The FCC has received a petition from the America's Carriers'
Telecommunications Association asking that we restrict the sale of
"Internet phone" software, because the providers of that software do
not comply with the rules that apply to telecommunications carriers.
Similar issues are being discussed in other countries, including
Canada.  We've just finished getting comments on that petition.  We're
in the process of reviewing those comments now, but I would just note
that the National Telecommunications and Information Administration,
the Administration's telecommunications expert, has filed very
thoughtful and well-reasoned comments with us asking us to reject this
petition.

I am also strongly inclined to believe that the right answer at this
time is not to place restrictions on software providers, or to subject
Internet telephony to the same rules that apply to conventional
circuit-switched voice carriers.  On the Internet, voice traffic is
just a particular kind of data, and imposing traditional regulatory
divisions on that data is both counterproductive and futile.  Even if
most of the FCC wasn't working around the clock on implementation of
the Telecommunications Act, I can't imagine that we would have the
time to keep track of all the bits passing over the Internet to
separate the "acceptable" data packets from the "unacceptable" voice
packets.

More importantly, we shouldn't be looking for ways to subject new
technologies to old rules.  Instead, we should be trying to fix the
old rules so that if those new technologies really are better, they
will flourish in the marketplace.  For years, some engineers have been
telling us that voice over a packet switched network wasn't possible.
The latency periods were too great, they said, and you'd never get
acceptable quality.  Well, it is going to be possible, and in the
short period of time since the first commercial products became
available, the quality has been rapidly improving.  But the last thing
we want to do is stop that improvement by thoughtless regulation.

Internet telephony may well become, in time, a competitive alternative
to traditional circuit-switched voice telephony.  After all, as the
growth of the cellular industry demonstrates, people are willing to
give up a significant level of quality in exchange for other benefits.
In the cellular case the benefit is the ability to make a call from
virtually anywhere, in the case of Internet telephony the benefit is a
vastly lower price.  This is especially true, for example, for
international telephone calls.

 ~=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=~=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=~-~=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=~=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=~
 Posted by Andrew Oram  - andyo@ora.com - Moderator: CYBER-RIGHTS
   A CPSR Project -- http://www.cpsr.org -- cpsr@cpsr.org
   Cyber-Rights:  http://www.cpsr.org/cpsr/nii/cyber-rights/
                  ftp://www.cpsr.org/cpsr/nii/cyber-rights/Library/
   CyberJournal:  (WWW or FTP) --&gt; ftp://ftp.iol.ie/users/rkmoore
 Materials may be reposted in their _entirety_ for non-commercial use.
 ~=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=~=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=~-~=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=~=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=~

</pre>

