    <h1>[3402] <a href="dl?thread=Re:+GeoCities+kills+web+site+with+drawings+of+male+nudes&after=3402">Re: GeoCities kills web site with drawings of male nudes</a></h1>
    <h2><i>jaed@best.com (Jeanne A. E. DeVoto)</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: Re: GeoCities kills web site with drawings of male nudes
<b>To</b>: j.stokes@student.anu.edu.au (Jason Stokes)
<b>From</b>: jaed@best.com (Jeanne A. E. DeVoto)
<b>Cc</b>: fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu
<b>Date</b>: Wed, 7 Aug 1996 22:29:55 -0700
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;v01540b01ae2f2ae41319@[205.149.167.81]&gt;

At 3:25 PM 8/8/96, Jason Stokes wrote:
&gt;Ok, true enough.  Also, perhaps they are confusing nudity with sexuality?
&gt;Of course, we can't tell, since they've just pulled the pages off the
&gt;server, in line with the eternal censors cry:

Actually, what I'm wondering is whether they got wind of the CDA or similar
local and state problems and clamped down in a panic over possible legal
liability. Given that they don't charge for the use of their website, they
may see this as a significant risk without corresponding benefit,
particularly if they are not well-informed about the details of the current
state of law.

Or it may be that the general public hysteria over "porno on the net" has
skewed their perceptions of what is and isn't acceptable to the audience
they hope to attract.

Or they may just be censorious buttheads. It's a possibility. But you'd
think they would have acted against these pages before now, if that were at
the bottom of this incident.

--
The Internet interprets the US Congress as system damage
and routes around it.   - with apologies to John Gilmore


