    <h1>[3426] <a href="dl?thread=Clinton+blasts+GOP+in+radio+addr+for+blocking+warrantless+wiretaps&after=3426">Clinton blasts GOP in radio addr for blocking warrantless wiretaps</a></h1>
    <h2><i>Declan McCullagh &lt;declan@eff.org&gt;</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: Clinton blasts GOP in radio addr for blocking warrantless wiretaps
<b>To</b>: fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu
<b>From</b>: Declan McCullagh &lt;declan@eff.org&gt;
<b>Date</b>: Sat, 10 Aug 1996 19:33:44 -0700 (PDT)
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;Pine.SUN.3.91.960810192932.3374B-100000@eff.org&gt;

[More of the same. *sigh* --Declan]


// declan@eff.org // I do not represent the EFF // declan@well.com //




    AllPolitics - News
   
             CLINTON: GOP LISTENING TO 'GUN LOBBY OVER LAW ENFORCEMENT'
                                          
   JACKSON, Wyo. (AllPolitics, Aug. 10) -- President Clinton on Saturday
   accused the Republican-led Congress of hampering efforts to fight terrorism
   by kowtowing to the gun lobby.
   
   In his weekly radio address from Jackson, where the president and his family
   are vacationing, Clinton said that Congress had stripped his anti-terrorism
   bill of valuable tools "that law enforcement needs to help them find out,
   track down and shut down terrorists."
   
   The president said that those who oppose two key provisions in his
   anti-terrorism legislation -- broader wiretapping authority and marking
   explosive powder with a "taggant" that can be traced back to the dealer who
   sold it -- were the same who opposed the Brady bill and the assault weapons
   ban.

[...]
   
   Negotiations between the White House and Congress for anti- terrorism
   legislation stalled last week over the wiretapping and explosive taggant
   issues. The House later passed an anti- terrorism bill of its own that
   excluded those provisions, but the Senate did not vote on the measure before
   adjourning for its August recess.
   
   The Republicans, the president said, were listening to "the gun lobby over
   law enforcement."
   
   "We cannot cast aside any tools in this fight for the security of our
   country and the safety of our people," he said.

[...]

</pre>

