    <h1>[3433] <a href="dl?thread=Re:+Clinton+on+Terrorism&after=3433">Re: Clinton on Terrorism</a></h1>
    <h2><i>jaed@best.com (Jeanne A. E. DeVoto)</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: Re: Clinton on Terrorism
<b>To</b>: "ERIC M. FREEDMAN, HOFSTRA LAW SCHOOL" &lt;lawemf@Vaxc.Hofstra.edu&gt;
<b>From</b>: jaed@best.com (Jeanne A. E. DeVoto)
<b>Cc</b>: fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu
<b>Date</b>: Mon, 12 Aug 1996 04:50:33 -0700
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;v01540b00ae34c908d946@[205.149.167.81]&gt;

At 11:16 PM 8/11/96, "ERIC M. FREEDMAN, HOFSTRA LAW SCHOOL"
&lt;lawemf@Vaxc.Hofstra.edu wrote:
&gt;Seems to me that it would be just as well to be discriminating in what we
&gt;say and to distinguish between the taggant provisions -- which strike me
&gt;as being perfectly appropriate legislation that is being blocked by
&gt;various groups including the NRA -- and the wiretap ones. -EMF

Um, well, except that
- there are serious safety questions concerning adding taggants to black
and smokeless powder
- a taggant provision is of dubious utility in catching terrorist bombers,
since black powder is not difficult to make (and presumably anyone serious
about planting pipe bombs and not getting caught would take this small
additional step for self-protection)
- it's hard to see how taggants would help LE track powder anyway, since
powder from a given manufacturing lot can be and commonly is shipped to
dealers all over the country.

I do think the issues are separable, and the wiretapping provisions are
obviously of considerably greater relevance to this list (and to
free-speech activism) than the taggant nonsense is. But I wanted to correct
the misapprehension; as we know from bitter experience with the CDA,
getting non-facts accepted as conventional wisdom is one of the first steps
in promulgating bad laws and in demonizing those who oppose them.

--
The Internet interprets the US Congress as system damage
and routes around it.   - with apologies to John Gilmore


</pre>

