<b>Date</b>: Thu, 8 Aug 1996 15:25:06 +1000
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;v01530500ae2fb6484914@[150.203.131.173]&gt;

On Wed, 7 Aug 1996 22:02:14 -0700, Jeanne A. E. DeVoto wrote:

&gt;Certainly, GeoCities has the right to determine which pages it decides to
&gt;sponsor. It may even have the right to offer the pages on on basis and then
&gt;pull them off under a new set of rules, after the page creator has invested
&gt;time in making them and publicizing their location. (I have the impression
&gt;from the initial message that this is what happened - can someone who knows
&gt;clarify this point?)
&gt;
&gt;However, that does not mean they're not slimy for causing this kind of
&gt;unnecessary inconvenience, and it doesn't mean they shouldn't be called on
&gt;their acts and others who might be considering dealing with them alerted to
&gt;the possibility of a problem.
&gt;
&gt;I personally would like to hear from GeoCities on why they chose to pull
&gt;the pages off. Did their policy change at any point, and if so, why did
&gt;they change it?

Ok, true enough.  Also, perhaps they are confusing nudity with sexuality?
Of course, we can't tell, since they've just pulled the pages off the
server, in line with the eternal censors cry:

"We've just protected you from horrible, noxious, obscene stuff!"
"How do I know?  Can I see it?"
"No, then we wouldn't be protecting you!"

Jason Stokes: j.stokes@student.anu.edu.au


</pre>

