    <h1>[3339] <a href="dl?thread=Re:+Your+attention+please....+(fwd)&after=3339">Re: Your attention please.... (fwd)</a></h1>
    <h2><i>declan@well.com (Declan McCullagh)</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: Re: Your attention please.... (fwd)
<b>To</b>: Andrew Kantor &lt;ak@mecklermedia.com&gt;
<b>From</b>: declan@well.com (Declan McCullagh)
<b>Cc</b>: fight-censorship@vorlon.mit.edu
<b>Date</b>: Wed, 31 Jul 1996 20:57:10 -0500
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;v01510112ae25bddda7d2@[204.62.128.229]&gt;

Andrew writes:

&gt;Let's keep this list about government censorship, please.

I like the way Tom Edwards, an avowed Libertarian, described it:

Institutional restrictions on speech also are often wrong, but the response
to them is different. Such muzzling attempts are not illegal, just
misguided.

However, we should keep in mind the very fuzzy difference distinction
between editing and censorship. Should, for instance, Jim Thomas be forced
to include off-topic rants in CuD? Should the National Coalition Against
Censorship be forced to publish similar materials in their quarterly
newsletter? Editing != censorship. The ALA has a definition of censorship
that may be useful here.

But perhaps we can agree that the most vile form of censorship remains that
done by governments, which buttress their laws with the power of guns,
tanks, and gallows.

-Declan


</pre>

