At 3:53 PM 7/31/96, Thomas Grant Edwards wrote:
&gt;I think that private electronic censorship is an appropriate topic for
&gt;fight-censorship...if we are to get along in a society based on
&gt;voluntary action, we need to communicate the deeds we feel are wrong,
&gt;even if they are legal.

If someone refuses to do business with another person based on disagreement
with his views or moral principles, that's certainly something to question,
but I can't see a single such incident as a problem. An inconvenience for
the artist who in this case has to find another, more reliable developer,
but no more than that. And I don't agree that it's wrong to refuse to do
business with someone, assuming you're not deceptive about it.

If we see a situation develop in which it's impossible to find developers
or printers to do certain work, or if there is an indication that this
developer refused this work because of intimidation or fear of legal
consequences, then it starts to become a censorship issue. But I didn't see
any such indications in the original message.

