	To be frank, I think very little of Libertarianism as a
political philosophy.  But more importantly, and somewhat relevant to
this list, I've come to believe that the habits of thought it engenders
are downright harmful, that they tend to keep people from thinking
effectively about the real world - which is a very complicated mix of
government, business, social customs, and so on, all interacting with
each other. In fact, I just wrote a long article where these very points
took up much of the space. Check out, at the Ethical Spectacle webzine,
(http://www.spectacle.org/)
   Linkname: Internet Blocking Programs and Privatized Censorship
        URL: http://www.spectacle.org/896/finkel.html

	Thus, I very much want to argue against such a worldview. I
don't view this as "flamebaiting", but as "political argument" (although
I am rough at times, but this is somewhat in anticipation of stock stuff
like being called a thief and a Stalinist). Given this background, what
are your suggestions as to what should be done?

