    <h1>[3355] <a href="dl?thread=Re:+Your+attention+please....+(fwd)&after=3355">Re: Your attention please.... (fwd)</a></h1>
    <h2><i>Bob B Chatelle &lt;kip@world.std.com&gt;</i></h2>
    <pre>
<b>Subject</b>: Re: Your attention please.... (fwd)
<b>To</b>: Jon Lebkowsky &lt;jonl@well.com&gt;
<b>From</b>: Bob B Chatelle &lt;kip@world.std.com&gt;
<b>Cc</b>: sethf@mit.edu, fight-censorship+@andrew.cmu.edu
<b>Date</b>: Thu, 1 Aug 1996 12:36:26 -0400 (EDT)
<b>In-reply-to</b>: &lt;<a href="/fight-censorship/dl?message-id=2.2.16.19960801110532.08d794c4@mail.well.com">2.2.16.19960801110532.08d794c4@mail.well.com</a>&gt;
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;Pine.SGI.3.93.960801122927.14374A-100000@world.std.com&gt;

For the sake of brevity, I will not quote Jon's reply to Seth's post.

Jon makes the valid point, which I'm sure Seth agrees with, that different
responses are appropriate for state and private censorship.  Most
importantly, when dealing with private censorship, one must not run to the
government for help.  If NBC suppresses a story critical of GE (its
owner), than the public has been denied access to important information.
But if we ask the government to dictate to NBC what they can and cannot
broadcast, then we trample upon the First Amendment.  The First Amendment
_protects_ private censorship (providing no other laws are broken).  Thus
when we respond to private censorship, we must respect the First Amendment
rights of the censors.  We can publicize the censorship incident, write
letters of protest, boycott, etc.  But  we must not involve the state in
regulating speech.

Cheers,
Bob


</pre>

