<b>Date</b>: Tue, 6 Aug 1996 21:49:48 -0700 (PDT)
<b>In-reply-to</b>: &lt;<a href="/fight-censorship/dl?message-id=v01510106ae2dcc02134a@[204.62.128.229]">v01510106ae2dcc02134a@[204.62.128.229]</a>&gt; from "Declan McCullagh" at Aug 6, 96 11:42:01 pm
<b>Message-id</b>: &lt;199608070449.VAA26426@remarkable.amazing.com&gt;

&gt; What you might want to do is publicize this well, and then move your site
&gt; to a less sensitive ISP such as Netcom.
&gt; 
&gt; Does anyone else have any insights?

I have a friend whose site containing nudity was treated in a very
similar way:  Wendy.

	http://www.geocities.com/Tokyo/4750

She had some beautifully tasteful partial nudes of herself on her
page; I would consider them erotic, not pornographic.  Unlike 
thie site in question here, I'd say that the main intent was to
show viewers a good time; there was essentially no content other
than the pictures.

When the hit counter went through the roof, they found her site and
apparently warned her a couple of times about its content not being
acceptable.  But she also played a mean trick on another Internet
user, which probably also contributed to her deletion.  It was apparently
some sort of revenge thing; I'm not sure who's right and who's wrong.
In my communications with her, I considered her a rather sweet lady
but not too frightfully verbal.  She certainly talked quite clearly
with her pictures, which revealed a stunningly perfect body.

I helped organize a brief protest campaign to Geocities which apparently
resulted in the reinstatement of her page, sans a few of the "best"
pictures.  And there, as far as I know, it remains.

The lesson from this would seem to be that you can probably get
Geocities to bend if you have enough friends.  (I probably don't
need to tell any of you here that being a gorgeous 25 year old girl
who loves to show off her body is one great way of acquiring
instant friends &lt;grin&gt;).

I hope this helps!

Best
D

</pre>

